 and the right to be heard. Adding to the playful, raucous mood of the barb-trading birds is Armitage, who at one point inserts himself into the poem as a “magistrate . . . to adjudicate”—one who is “skilled with words & worldly wise / & frowns on every form of vice.”Featuring the Middle English text on facing pages and an introduction by Armitage, this volume will delight readers of all ages.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBirdsvPoetry. 0aDebate poetry, English (Middle)vTranslations into English. 0aDebate poetry, English (Middle). 7aPOETRY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAbortion debate.  aAdage.  aAddiction.  aAdultery.  aAmbiguity.  aAnathema.  aAstrology.  aAunt.  aCrone.  aDisgust.  aDoomsday cult.  aDunce.  aEmbarrassment.  aEnglish alphabet.  aErudition.  aExtremism.  aFacebook.  aFoe (novel).  aGod.  aGrandparent.  aHarassment.  aHis Woman.  aI Wish (manhwa).  aIllegal immigration.  aIn Death.  aIn the Bedroom.  aInformation scientist.  aInsect.  aInstagram.  aLament.  aLeon Festinger.  aLiterature.  aMany Moons.  aMedieval poetry.  aMisery (novel).  aMisfortune (folk tale).  aMonologue.  aNarrative.  aNew Democrats.  aNickname.  aNorbert Elias.  aOath.  aObservation.  aOpportunism.  aParody.  aPastiche.  aPerson of color.  aPity.  aPoetry.  aPolitical football.  aProfanity.  aProverb.  aRacism.  aRidicule.  aRodent.  aSinging.  aSocial environment.  aSuperiority (short story).  aThe Owl and the Nightingale.  aThis Country.  aTit (bird).  aTranssexual.  aTrickster.  aTwitter.  aTwo Birds (Awake).  aUncertainty.  aWarfare.  aWilliam the Conqueror.  aYogh.  aYokel.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is 